    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 24px;max-width:70ch;">Six workstreams, every month, every engagement &mdash; not just a bank reconciliation called &ldquo;the close.&rdquo;</p>
    <div class="r-3">
      {%- for d in included %}
      <div class="dc-card"><span class="eyebrow" style="display:block;margin-bottom:8px;">{{ d.num }}</span><h3>{{ d.name | safe }}</h3><p class="prose" style="font-size:14.5px;margin:6px 0 0;">{{ d.body | safe }}</p></div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="sec reveal" id="acct-monthend-signals">
  <div class="ct">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">When a real close earns its keep</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:10px;">If any of these sound familiar, the answer is yes.</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 24px;max-width:70ch;">Most owners reach for a structured close when &ldquo;the books are pretty much done&rdquo; stops being good enough.</p>
    <div class="r-3">
      {%- for s in signals %}
      <div class="dc-card"><h3>{{ s.opener | safe }}</h3><p class="prose" style="font-size:14.5px;margin:6px 0 0;">{{ s.body | safe }}</p></div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="acct-monthend-process" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">The close calendar</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:10px;">A predictable cadence every month.</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 24px;max-width:70ch;">The published close calendar makes the process visible to your team and your CPA &mdash; same shape, every month.</p>
    <div class="process-grid">
      {%- for s in process %}
      <div class="process-step"><div class="process-step__n{% if loop.last %} process-step__n--done{% endif %}">{{ s.num | safe }}</div><h3>{{ s.name | safe }}</h3><p>{{ s.body | safe }}</p></div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="sec reveal" id="acct-monthend-cadence-table">
  <div class="ct">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">The published calendar, day by day</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:10px;">When each step happens after month-end.</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 24px;max-width:70ch;">A typical close runs 5&ndash;10 business days after month-end. The windows below are the same every month, so your team and CPA know what lands when.</p>
    <table class="cmp">
      <caption class="sr-only">Month-end close calendar — window, workstream, and what is delivered</caption>
      <thead><tr><th scope="col">Window</th><th scope="col">Workstream</th><th scope="col">What happens</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        {%- for r in cadenceTable %}
        <tr><th scope="row" data-col="Window">{{ r.window | safe }}</th><td data-col="Workstream">{{ r.work | safe }}</td><td data-col="What happens">{{ r.detail | safe }}</td></tr>
        {%- endfor %}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="acct-monthend-boundary" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Where the close stops</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">Bookkeeping and close &mdash; coordinated with your CPA, not replacing one.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Month-end close is <strong>bookkeeping and management accounting</strong>: reconciliations, accruals, journal entries, and internal financial statements delivered on a calendar. It is <strong>not</strong> an external <a href="/legal/disclaimer/">audit, review, or compilation</a> &mdash; those are licensed CPA engagements with their own independence and reporting standards. TechBrot delivers internal management and CPA-ready statements; we coordinate with your CPA or EA for tax filing and any formal engagement.</p>
      <p>That boundary is what keeps the work honest. A clean close hands your CPA reconciled, locked books so January is a filing exercise &mdash; not a reconstruction. Where a past period was never closed, that&rsquo;s a <a href="/accounting/bookkeeping/catch-up-bookkeeping/?intent=catch-up">catch-up</a> or <a href="/accounting/bookkeeping/cleanup-bookkeeping/?intent=cleanup">cleanup</a> engagement first; once the past is rebuilt and reconciled, you transition into a recurring monthly close on a published calendar.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="sec reveal" id="acct-monthend-beyond">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Beyond the close</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">A clean close is what makes every other report worth anything.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Forecasts, KPIs, performance reviews, budgets &mdash; none of it works on unreconciled books. The close is the discipline that makes the whole reporting and advisory layer trustworthy. Skip the close and every number above it is provisional; do the close right and the rest of the practice has a real foundation.</p>
      <p>Most TechBrot clients run the close inside <a href="/accounting/bookkeeping/monthly-bookkeeping/?intent=monthly">monthly bookkeeping</a> and then layer <a href="/accounting/advisory/?intent=advisory">advisory</a> on top &mdash; <a href="/accounting/advisory/kpi-reporting/?intent=advisory">KPI reporting</a>, <a href="/accounting/advisory/cash-flow-management/?intent=cash-flow">cash flow</a>, performance reviews, up to a <a href="/accounting/advisory/fractional-cfo/?intent=fractional-cfo">fractional CFO</a> seat. As automation handles the routine, the close is the operational discipline that earns the right to do everything else.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

